[1] Philippines (National Capital Region)
Date: Wed 31 Jan 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Manila Standard Today - Manila, Philippines [edited]
<http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/?page=police2_jan31_2007>

As of Wed 31 Jan 2007, at least 27 persons with dengue fever, who
were admitted in January [2007] alone, remained confined at the Rizal
Medical Center in Pasig City.
Hospital records stated that the latest patient admitted Monday night
[29 Jan 2007] was from Fort Bonifacio in Taguig City, and whom
doctors diagnosed as suffering from Stage-2 dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF].
No casualties have been reported among the patients coming from the
cities of Taguig, Pasig and Makati, and the towns of Taytay and
Cainta in Rizal province.
Meanwhile, Health Secretary Francisco Duque III said he has ordered
his department to mobilize all available resources to tackle dengue
under an annual program. "Dengue is no longer a seasonal disease. It
is now spreading all year round. This has been the trend in our
neighboring countries," Duque said.
He said other tropical countries in the Southeast Asian region,
including Thailand and Vietnam, have recorded a rise in dengue cases
recently. Even Singapore, which he described as a clean city,
indicated a doubling of dengue cases in 2005 and 2006.
Duque said he has ordered the health department to prepare for a
12-month coverage against the disease, spread by mosquitoes that
breed in stagnant water.
"We have to adjust our campaign against dengue. I have ordered the
DOH to mobilize all resources to stop it," he said.
[Byline: Florante S. Solmerin]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The indications of year-around transmission of dengue virus in this
area are not good news. If this proves to be correct, local health
authorities will have to mount a vector control campaign throughout
the year. Public education will become critical to inform people of
the risks of water storage in and immediately around their residences
and places of business.
