[2] Philippines (Negros Oriental)
Date: Thu 1 Feb 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Philippine Information Agency - Philippines [edited]
<http://www.pia.gov.ph/?m=12&fi=p070201.htm&no=50&r=&y=&mo=>

The Department of Health (DOH <http://www.doh.gov.ph/>) in Dumaguete
City reported a decrease in the number of dengue cases recorded in
Negros Oriental in 2006. Data collected by the DOH shows that dengue
cases in the province dipped to 978 last year [2006] from 1203 cases
recorded in 2005.
The mosquito-borne disease, however, left a more deadly trail in 2006
with 8 deaths recorded compared to 6 victims who died in 2005.
According to Suzy Sayre, Provincial Mosquito-Borne Disease Program
Coordinator of DOH, the casualties in 2006 were from Bacong, Bais
City, Dumaguete City, La Libertad, Mabinay, and Tanjay City. Sayre
said the areas most affected by the killer disease are mostly urban
areas such as the cities of Tanjay, Bais, and Dumaguete. "Dengue is
known as an urban disease," said Sayre.
The DOH surveillance team is now monitoring dengue cases as of
January 2007. Sayre said she is unable to divulge just yet the exact
number of dengue cases for January 2007 as surveillance work is still
being done.
She said the DOH continues to conduct intervention measures such as
regular health information drive, environmental sanitation, and
container management in all areas and Rural Health Units in the province.
DOH National Epidemiology Center Director Dr. Eric Tayag has recently
assured that DOH is at the forefront of the dengue outbreak in
Lagusan and Agusan del Sur.
Local officials of San Pedro, Laguna, have earlier declared a dengue
outbreak in their municipality following the death of a person and
the hospitalization of some 20 persons. The DOH is seriously
monitoring the condition of the victims while the Laguna Health
Office is currently conducting fogging operations to contain the
proliferation of dengue-carrying mosquitoes.
A dengue outbreak has also been declared in Bayugan, Agusan del Sur,
where 3 persons died and 18 persons were hospitalized. DOH said that
the numbers of dengue victims in Bayugan continues to rise but
assures the public that the DOH remains at the forefront in making
sure that all the victims receive immediate medical attention.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED thanks Joseph Dudley for submitting the same report. In a
previous post concerning dengue in the Philippines (PRO/EDR>
Dengue/DHF Update 2007 (04) 20070127.0364), ProMED requested
information about the "bandillo system" that was activated for local
dengue control. A-Lan Banks provided the following explanation, "From
what I can gather, a "bandillo" is a word in Cuyunon that means 'town
crier.'" Apparently, the role is usually taken by a policeman who
relays the information. I guess that makes sense in the context of
the dengue outbreak." - Mod.TY]
