[3] Philippines (Countrywide)
Date: Thu 1 Feb 2007
From: Joseph Dudley
Source: Philippines Information Agency [edited]
<http://www.pia.gov.ph/?m=12&fi=p070201.htm&no=51>

The mosquito-born-disease, dengue fever, has become prevalent in
urban dwellings these past few years not only in the Philippines but
also in the whole Asian region.
Dengue cases have reached alarming highs this January [2007] and the
Government will exhaust all means to combat the disease and contain
the outbreak. Because of this, the Department of Health (DOH) is
embarking on an intensified battle to fight the alarming increase of
dengue cases.
In San Lazaro Hospital alone, 189 dengue cases have so far been
listed. Other areas with dengue cases are Marikina, Rizal, Pasig,
Laguna, Agusan del Sur, Cagayan de Oro, Osamis, and Bukidnon.
Central Visayas recorded its highest number in 2005, with 3306
reported cases. Cebu province reported the most number of cases --
2313 and 75 fatalities. Bohol recorded 299 cases, 10 of which
resulted in death. Negros Oriental had 633 cases with 6 fatalities.
Siquijor has no exact figure, but DOH reported it has the lowest
recorded cases in the region.
Dr. Lakshmi Legaspi, assistant director of the Department of Health
7, said the months of June to August are considered the most
problematic, with persistent rains during these months providing
numerous breeding areas for the mosquito that carries the virus.
DOH Secretary Francisco Duque enjoins the public to maintain a clean
environment to avoid this disease. He asks the public to help the
health department contain the outbreak by means of a cleanup campaign
to destroy mosquito-breeding sites. Destroying of mosquito breeding
sites entails cleaning and removing containers that collect water;
burning, burying disposed containers, and covering water vats, drums,
and buckets.
Water containers should be washed out at least once a week. Per DOH,
it is appropriate to use insecticide or larvicide in ponds and
low-lying areas to kill mosquito larvae.
[Byline: Mimi Bern Edaga]
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
